step.context:
\text{The following trigonometric identity would}\\
\text{help reduce }\dfrac{\cos 2 x- \cos 2 \alpha}{\cos x - \cos \alpha}
\text{ to }2(\cos x + \cos\alpha)

step.tex:
\begin{align}
  &\int 2 ( \cos x + \cos \alpha)  \, dx \quad \\
  &= 2 \int \cos x \, dx + 2\int \cos \alpha \, dx \\
  &= 2(\sin  x + x\cos\alpha)+C
\end{align}

\begin{align}
  &\int 2 ( \cos x + \cos \alpha)  \, dx \quad \\
  &= 2 \int \cos x \, dx + 2\int \cos \alpha \, dx \\
  &= 2(\sin  x + \sin\alpha)+C
\end{align}

step.reason:
\int \cos (a x)dx = \dfrac{\sin (a x)}{a}+ C \text{, but}\\
\int \cos a\,dx = \cos a\, x +C \\
\text{$\cos a$ is a constant, not a function of x.}
